The Kentucky Cardiovascular Disease Initiative (KCDI) is hereby created with the program goals that include but are not limited to:
Preventing and reducing the prevalence of cardiovascular disease in Kentucky through early detection and education;
Reducing the incidence of deaths from cardiovascular disease in Kentucky;
Measurably reducing health-care costs associated with cardiovascular disease in Kentucky;
Conducting research and developing new intellectual property and ancillary health businesses that create new knowledge-based businesses in Kentucky;
Improving access to best practices and protocols for cardiovascular disease for all Kentuckians through an e-health network; and
Assisting in securing state, federal, and private funding to stimulate health information capacities.

The KCDI shall be governed by a board that shall be appointed by the secretary of the Cabinet for Health and Family Services, except as provided in paragraphs (q) to (s) of this subsection, no later than August 1, 2007, and composed of:
One (1) member shall be appointed by the secretary of the Cabinet for Health and Family Services who shall serve as chair of the KCDI during the first year, and this individual shall remain as a board member for two (2) additional years. The board shall elect its chair after the first year and may reelect the current chair;
The president of the University of Louisville, or a designee;
The president of the University of Kentucky, or a designee;
The secretary or designee of the Cabinet for Health and Family Services;
The commissioner or designee of the Department of Commercialization and Innovation;
The commissioner or designee of the Department for Public Health;
The commissioner or designee of the Department of Insurance;
The chair of the Kentucky e-Health Network Board, or a designee;
One (1) representative of a Kentucky comprehensive university and one (1) representative of the Kentucky Community and Technical College System;
Two (2) physicians with experience in research and treatment of cardiovascular disease, one (1) recommended by the dean of the medical school at the University of Louisville and one (1) recommended by the dean of the medical school at the University of Kentucky;
The executive director of the Kentucky Primary Care Association;
The president of the Kentucky Academy of Family Physicians;
One (1) member of a Kentucky chapter of the American Heart Association;
Four (4) members representing the business community, from a list of eight (8) persons recommended by the Kentucky Chamber of Commerce;
Four (4) members representing private sector hospitals that treat the greatest number of cardiology patients as measured by the number of MDC 5 discharges and as reported by COMPdata or its successor;
One (1) representative from a freestanding pediatric teaching hospital;
One (1) at-large member appointed by the Governor;
Two (2) members of the Senate, one (1) representing each major political party, appointed by the President of the Senate; and
Two (2) members of the House of Representatives, one (1) representing each major political party appointed by the Speaker of the House.
